   \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $V^{M+N}_{0}=[ 3m+\mathrm{max}\,( m,\, e) ] / 4+n-be/ 4.$ \end{document}

This proposition implies that trading on ε only is always an equilibrium strategy, even when the two units are integrated. In this case, the stock price partially reveals information about ε, while the information about δ is fully suppressed. Consequently, the improvement of investment decisions can be achieved only in unitM, whose investment payoff is the same as in the spin‐off case,
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $[ 3m+\mathrm{max}\,( m,\, e) ] / 4$ \end{document}
               . Since information aboutNis not revealed, the expected payoff of unitNis its unconditional NPV,n. The value of the integrated firm at time 0 is the sum of the payoffs of these two units minus the uninformed investors’ expected loss to the informed trader ℐ.

