sec.p:
Next we consider case iii, where both types of information are collected. Notice that the strategy space has been augmented because trading strategies can be made contingent on four possible states corresponding to the four possible realizations of the
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $( \varepsilon ,\,\delta ) $ \end{document}
               pair. Again, in order to prevent trader ℐ’s trades from being fully revealing, there has to be some kind of link between his trades in the four different states (this puts restrictions on his trading strategies). Similar to our previous discussion, there are generally two ways to link (pool) any two of the four states: (1) the informed trader’s order in one state isbplus that in the other state so that when the liquidity shock is absent, the total order flow looks the same as that in the other state when the liquidity shock is present; (2) the informed trader’s order in each of the two states is the same.

