               . That is,

               Notice that this condition depends mainly on the “mean return” (mandn) and the “variance” (ε and δ) of the investment opportunities of the two business units.

We are now going to address the following questions: What type of firms are most likely to be involved in conglomerate mergers? What type of firms are most likely to be spun off? To answer these questions, we need to classify firms along the means and variances of their investment opportunities. To do this, we impose the following ordering on the parameters:



                        Assumption2. 
                           \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $e> m> d> n\geq 0.$ \end{document}

The ordering in assumption 2 enables us to obtain a simple classification of business units. We can characterize the real‐world business units into four types by pairing up two possible means (mandn) and two possible volatilities (ε and δ) of their investment opportunities:


Type 1 (the high‐return, high‐risk type): (m, ε);



Type 2 (the high‐return, low‐risk type): (m, δ);



Type 3 (the low‐return, high‐risk type): (n, ε);



Type 4 (the low‐return, low‐risk type): (n, δ).

We consider a merger (or a spin‐off) between any two of these four types of firms. To simplify the analysis, we also make the assumption that allows us to focus on the case in which only information about ε is collected after a merger:22




                        Assumption3. 
                           \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $c\geq c^{*}.$ \end{document}

These merger gains (or losses, if negative) between any two types of units,
