Intuitively, the low‐return, high‐risk type firm stands to gain the most from a more efficient investment decision. Staying focused helps to improve its decision through more information revelation. The converse is true for the high‐return, low‐risk type firm. Specifically, for the former type of firm only, information acquisition generates value, since the information observed by the informed trader guides the capital allocation process. In the latter case, even though the stock price becomes more informative, it does not affect the capital allocation decisions of the firm. Because
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $m< e,$ \end{document}
               the condition in the second part of proposition 6 holds when the liquidity shockbis not too large.

fn.p:
The condition becomes
