                  is higher than
                     \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $c^{*}$ \end{document}
                  , reflecting the fact that the informed trader who can acquire type δ information is more likely to do so when he does not coordinate his strategy with the one who can acquire type ε information. We will provide these results to interested readers upon request.

app.p:
Intable A1, all possible strategies that are not fully revealing are listed lexicographically (see the Remark immediately following this proof). Based ontable A1, we then compute the informed trader’s potential trading profit for each of these strategies. The calculations are similar to those in proposition 1. Note that for some strategies, the informed trading profit varies in different parameter regions. That is, the trading profit depends on the relative magnitude between
